# üêû bug report

### Affected Package
The issued is caused by package @angular/compiler-cli

### Is this a regression?
No

### Description
Note: PR #22856 by @jeffora lay the groundwork for proper barrel file support

Right now, any path depth with barrel files fails because `MetadataBundler.resolveModuleName` and a few other methods do not keep track of the parent paths, mostly leading to intermediate paths disappearing.

With the following example, no decorator metadata gets added to metadata.json file, and the `MetadataBundler` processes `repro.module` as if it was at `src/repro.module.ts` rather than `src/lib/repro.module.ts` (because `path.dirname(from)` returns `.` for `./lib`, thus losing the path in the process when then joining with `repro.module`).

<pre><code>
// src/public-api.ts
import * from './lib';

// src/lib/index.ts
export {ReproModule} from './repro.module';

// src/lib/repro.module.ts
import {NgModule} from '@angular/core';
@NgModule({})
class ReproModule;
export {ReproModule};
</code></pre>

This is only the case for metadata retrieval, the classes/etc. are properly exported. The metadata.json does not hold any metadata information though.

Without barrel files, the metadata.json file is (html tags removed):

<pre><code>
{
    "__symbolic": "module",
    "version": 4,
    "metadata": {
        "ReproService": {
            "__symbolic": "class",
            "decorators": [{
                "__symbolic": "call",
                "expression": {
                    "__symbolic": "reference",
                    "module": "@angular/core",
                    "name": "Injectable",
                    "line": 2,
                    "character": 1
                },
                "arguments": [{
                    "providedIn":"root"
                }]
            }],
           "members": {
               "__ctor__": [{
                   "__symbolic": "constructor"
               }]
            },
            "statics": {
                "ngInjectableDef": {}
            }
        },
       ....
}
</code></pre>

With barrel files, the metadata.json file is:

<pre><code>
{
    "__symbolic": "module",
    "version": 4,
    "exports": [{
        "from": "./repro.service"
    }, {
        "from": "./repro.component"
    }, {
        "from": "./repro.module"
    }],
    "metadata": {},
    "origins": {},
    "importAs": "repro"
}
</code></pre>

## üî¨ Minimal Reproduction
<pre><code>
git clone https://github.com/rraziel/ngc-barrel-repo
cd ngc-barrel-repo; npm i
ng build repro
cat dist/repro/repro.metadata.json
</code></pre>

The project was created with:
<pre><code>
ng new ngc-barrel-repro
ng generate library repro
add an index.ts next to repro.module.ts that exports what is exported from public-api.ts
modify public-api.ts to use index.ts implicitly
</code></pre>

Relevant files:
- https://github.com/rraziel/ngc-barrel-repo/blob/master/projects/repro/src/public-api.ts
- https://github.com/rraziel/ngc-barrel-repo/blob/master/projects/repro/src/lib/index.ts

## üî• Exception or Error
The generated *metadata.json file does not contain metadata information (e.g. the NgModule decorator).
Many other issues can also arise depending on how files are imported and generally end up with undefined error messages (undefined module, duplicate undefined keys, etc.).

